\section*{2 Normal blood cells I: Red cells and platelets}

\section*{Peripheral blood cells}

Normal peripheral blood contains mainly mature cells which do not undergo further division.

\section*{Red cells (erythrocytes)}

Red cells contain haemoglobin ( Hb ) which allows them to carry oxygen ( $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ ) and carbon dioxide ( $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ ). Haemoglobin is composed of four polypeptide globin chains each with an iron containing haem molecule (Fig. 2.1). Embryonic haemoglobins (Portland, Gower I and II) are present in early fetal life, fetal haemoglobin ( Hb F ) dominates by late fetal life (Table 2.1). A switch occurs at 3-6 months in the neonatal period to normal adult haemoglobin ( Hb A ) (Fig. 2.2). The ability of haemoglobin to bind $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ is measured as the haemoglobin- $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ dissociation curve. Raised concentrations of $2,3-\mathrm{DPG}, \mathrm{H}^{+}$ions or $\mathrm{CO}_{2}$ decrease $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ affinity, allowing more $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ delivery to tissues (Fig. 2.3). Hb F has a higher, and sickle $\mathrm{Hb}(\mathrm{Hb} \mathrm{S})$ a lower $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ affinity than Hb A . Erythropoietin controls the production of red cells. It is produced in the peritubular complex of the kidney ( $90 \%$ ), liver and other organs. Erythropoietin stimulates mixed lineage and red cell progenitors as well as pronormoblasts and early erythroblasts to proliferate, differentiate and produce haemoglobin (Table 2.2). Erythropoietin secretion is stimulated by reduced $\mathrm{O}_{2}$ supply to the kidney receptor (see Chapter 27, Table 27.1).

