\section*{Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR)}

This measures the rate of fall of a column of red cells in plasma in 1 h . It is largely determined by plasma concentrations of proteins, especially fibrinogen and globulins. It is raised in anaemia. Normal range rises with age. A raised ESR is a non-specific indicator of an acute phase response and is of value in monitoring disease activity (e.g. rheumatoid arthritis). A raised ESR occurs in inflammatory disorders, infections, malignancy, myeloma, anaemia and pregnancy. The plasma viscosity gives comparable information and is increasingly favoured as it can be easily automated. C-reactive protein (CRP) is raised in an acute phase response and is valuable in monitoring this. Whole blood viscosity is also influenced by the cell counts, and is therefore raised when the red cell count (erythrocrit), white cells count (leucocrit) or platelet count is grossly raised.

