\section*{11 Megaloblastic anaemia I: Vitamin $\mathbf{B}_{\mathbf{1 2}}$ deficiency}

Megaloblastic anaemia (MA) is associated with an abnormal appearance of the bone marrow erythroblasts in which nuclear development is delayed and nuclear chromatin has a lacy open appearance. There is a defect in DNA synthesis usually caused by deficiency of vitamin $B_{12}\left(B_{12}\right.$, cobalamin) or folate.

\section*{Biochemical basis}

Folate is an essential coenzyme for the synthesis of thymidine monosphosphate (TMP) and therefore of DNA. $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ is a coenzyme for methionine synthase, a reaction needed in the demethylation of the plasma form of folate, 5-methyltetrahydrofolate (methylTHF) (Fig. 11.1). MethylTHF enters cells and its demethylation provides THF which acts as substrate for synthesis of intracellular folate, polyglutamates, the coenzyme forms of folate needed in DNA synthesis.
$\mathbf{B}_{12}$ physiology (Fig. 11.2)
- Adult daily requirement for $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ is $1 \mu \mathrm{~g}$ (normal mixed
diet contains $10-15 \mu \mathrm{~g}$ ). $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ is present only in foods of animal origin: meat, fish, eggs, milk and butter; it is absent from vegetables, cereals and fruit, unless contaminated by microorganisms. Normal body stores of $\mathrm{B}_{12}$, largely in the liver with an enterohepatic circulation, are sufficient to last for 2-4 years.
- Dietary $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ after release from food and gastric ' R ' binder (see below) combines with intrinsic factor (IF) secreted by gastric parietal cells (GPC). IF-B ${ }_{12}$ complex attaches to ileal receptors and $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ is absorbed.
- Passive absorption (about $0.1 \%$ of oral $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ ) occurs through buccal, gastric and duodenal mucosae.
- Absorbed $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ attaches to transcobalamin (TC) II which carries $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ in plasma to the liver, bone marrow, brain and other tissues. Most $B_{12}$ in plasma is attached to a second $B_{12}$ binding protein, TC I, and is functionally inactive. TC I is synthesized by granulocytes and their precursors. Similar glycoproteins ('R' proteins) occur in saliva, gastric juice and milk.

