- Gastrectomy (total or subtotal) leads to $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ deficiency.
- Congenital IF deficiency or abnormality is rare.

\section*{Intestinal causes}

These include bacterial (rarely fish tapeworm) colonization of small intestine, stagnant loop syndromes, congenital and acquired defects of the ileum (e.g. ileal resection, Crohn's disease). Congenital $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ malabsorption with proteinuria is rare.

\section*{Clinical features}
- Gradual onset of features of anaemia.
- Mild jaundice, caused by ineffective erythropoiesis.
- Glossitis and angular cheilosis and, if severe, sterility (either sex) and reversible melanin skin pigmentation.
- $B_{12}$ deficiency causes a symmetrical neuropathy affecting the pyramidal tracts and posterior columns of the spinal cord (subacute combined degeneration of the cord) and the peripheral nerves. Patients present with tingling in the feet (more than the hands), difficulty in gait, visual or psychiatric disorders.
- $\mathrm{B}_{12}$ or folate deficiency are associated with increased plasma homocysteine which is associated with arterial and venous thrombosis and, if pregnant, to an increased incidence of fetal neural tube defects.
- Patients may be asymptomatic and detected by a routine blood test.

