\section*{Alloimmune haemolytic anaemia}

This is caused when antibody produced by one individual reacts against red cells of another. The three important situations are:
1 mismatched blood transfusions (see Chapter 37);
2 haemolytic disease of the newborn (see Chapter 37); and
3 following marrow or solid organ transplantation.

\section*{Drug-induced immune haemolytic anaemia}

Mechanisms include the following.
- Antibody directed against a drug (e.g. penicillin)-red cell membrane complex, the drug acting as a hapten.
- Antibody against a drug (e.g. quinidine)-plasma protein complex with subsequent deposition of the immune complex on red cells.
- Stimulation of autoantibody (warm type) production against the red cell, e.g. methyldopa, fludarabine.

