This is a one or two $\alpha$ gene deletion with microscopic hypochromic red cells with raised red cell count ( $>5.5 \times 10^{9} / \mathrm{L}$ ). Mild anaemia occurs in some cases with two $\alpha$ genes deleted.

\section*{$\beta$-thalassaemia}

\section*{Thalassaemia major}

Complete ( $\beta$ o) or almost complete ( $\beta^{+}$) failure of $\beta$-globin chain synthesis resulting from one of over 160 different point mutations or deletions in the $\beta$-globin gene or its controlling sequences on chromosome 11. There is severe imbalance of $\alpha: \beta+\gamma$ chains with deposition of $\alpha$ chains in erythroblasts, ineffective erythropoiesis, severe anaemia and extramedullary haemopoiesis.

\section*{Clinical features}
- Anaemia presents at the age of 3-6 months when the switch from $\alpha$ - to $\beta$-chain synthesis normally occurs. Milder cases present later (up to age 4 years).
- Failure to thrive, intercurrent infection, pallor, mild jaundice.
- Enlargement of the liver and spleen, expansion of the bones - especially of the skull - with bossing and a 'hair on

