- Blood film shows sickle cells, target cells and often features of splenic atrophy (see Fig.17.1).
- Screening tests for sickling demonstrate increased turbidity of the blood after deoxygenation (e.g. with dithionate or $\mathrm{Na}_{2} \mathrm{HPO}_{4}$ ). Haemoglobin electrophoresis (Fig. 17.5) shows haemoglobin with an abnormal migration. In Hb SS there is absence of $\mathrm{Hb} \mathrm{A} . \mathrm{Hb} \mathrm{F}$ level is usually mildly raised ( $5-10 \%$ ).

