\section*{Sickle cell trait}

Sickle cell trait is a benign condition without anaemia and is usually asymptomatic. Occasionally haematuria or overt crisis occurs. Genetic counselling should be offered to carriers.

\section*{Other sickling disorders}

Haemoglobin S may occur in combination with other genetic defects of haemoglobin (compound heterozygotes). $\mathrm{Hb} \mathrm{S} / \beta$-thalassaemia (Fig. 17.3) clinically resembles Hb SS but the spleen usually remains enlarged and MCV is reduced. Hb SC (Fig. 17.4) disease varies in severity from mild to indistinguishable from sickle cell anaemia; thrombotic complications are particularly common.

\section*{Other structural haemoglobin abnormalities}

Many other mutations of the $\alpha$ - or $\beta$-chain genes have been identified. Most that have a significant population frequency are not associated with clinical symptoms.

